## Summary

I have a layout where I want to ignore an optional section. There is currently no way to do this, IgnoreSection will always throw if the section is not defined.

## Detailed design

Mirror what we have for RenderSection onto IgnoreSection:

```csharp
public abstract class RazorPage
{
   // Existing API
   public HtmlString RenderSection(string name) {}
   HtmlString RenderSection(string name, bool required) {}
   public void IgnoreSection(string sectionName) {}

   // API Addition
   public void IgnoreSection(string sectionName, bool required) {}
}
```

 [Microsoft framework design guidelines](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/design-guidelines/base-classes-for-implementing-abstractions) stated that:

> ❌ AVOID naming base classes with a "Base" suffix if the class is intended for use in public APIs.

My question is: why the ASP.NET Core team violated their own guideline?

Secondly wouldn't the following design have been more meaningful?

```
// The base class for the MVC and API controllers which will contain all the common functionalities.
internal class Controller
{
}

// Will add the MVC specific functionalities and behaviour
public class MvcController: Controller
{
}

// Will add the API specific functionalities and behaviour
public class ApiController: Controller
{
}
```

Thank you.

